<subSubSection id="EFB6D4C7F62BE5B4925F492F73EB420B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="2D2A39FD5D5DB946F9B06CE57DD118C8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="359F1E0FD1E76184E8D3E6614D35251E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5E7621CD04AC5D9D09B5D34EE61E7FEA" class="Insecta" family="Gelsemiaceae" genus="Phytomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phytomyza ilicicola" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ilicicola">
<emphasis id="E8540112ED359F37291A9CE026D1899A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phytomyza ilicicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is collected with relative frequency compared to other holly-mining agromyzids in the Delmarva states, all of which belong to the 
<taxonomicName id="18A7FD139BEAAEE239A181A535B25368" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. ilicis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="ilicis">
<emphasis id="3804B4AE7A4CA305BCFF998C459174F0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. ilicis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. This group was recently revised in North America by 
<bibRefCitation id="61939E7DCE941F987346849FBD5AC139" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1183 - 1206" refId="B145" refString="Lonsdale, O, Scheffer, SJ, 2011. Revision of the Holly leaf-miners in the Nearctic (Phytomyza: Agromyzidae). Annals of the Entomological Society of America 104 (6): 1183 - 1206, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" title="Revision of the Holly leaf-miners in the Nearctic (Phytomyza: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" volume="104" year="2011">Lonsdale and Scheffer (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, who included discussions on life history and host use. This followed molecular treatments of the group by 
<bibRefCitation id="33F8F4768EDDFCE78A9FEEF244044EA1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1006/mpev.2000.0830" author="Scheffer, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="244 - 255" refId="B221" refString="Scheffer, SJ, Wiegmann, BM, 2000. Molecular phylogenetics of the holly leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae: Phytomyza): Species limits, speciation and dietary specialization. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 17: 244 - 255, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1006/mpev.2000.0830" title="Molecular phylogenetics of the holly leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae: Phytomyza): Species limits, speciation and dietary specialization." url="https://doi.org/10.1006/mpev.2000.0830" volume="17" year="2000">Scheffer and Wiegmann (2000)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="3F127EB6CD8D29D2E34AB7DEFCDD312C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2007.03303.x" author="Scheffer, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="2627 - 2637" refId="B216" refString="Scheffer, SJ, Hawthorne, DJ, 2007. Molecular evidence of host-associated genetic divergence in the holly leafminer Phytomyza glabricola (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Apparent discordance among marker systems. Molecular Ecology 16: 2627 - 2637, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2007.03303.x" title="Molecular evidence of host-associated genetic divergence in the holly leafminer Phytomyza glabricola (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Apparent discordance among marker systems." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-294X.2007.03303.x" volume="16" year="2007">Scheffer and Hawthorne (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, and the description of a related species feeding on 
<taxonomicName id="A90408C40D322D007A4B958A86870091" authorityName="A.L.Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gelsemiaceae" genus="Gelsemium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Gelsemium" order="Rubiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F843CA763B25FEF8FA2BEB486DED26EF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gelsemium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="366C1E48617E26139A3ABCAB4C5C92FF" authorityName="A.L.Jussieu" authorityYear="1789" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gelsemiaceae" genus="Gelsemium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Rubiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Spermatophyta" rank="family">Gelsemiaceae</taxonomicName>
) in North Carolina, 
<taxonomicName id="604BE3904B6B618AB18EBBB923C65CCC" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. omlandi" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="omlandi">
<emphasis id="852B50D1EC157FC9BB459EF4354FD6FC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. omlandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Scheffer and Lonsdale (
<bibRefCitation id="51D44B7417F0630A4C8500CA6ADB4B11" DOI="https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.113.1.42" author="Scheffer, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="42 - 49" refId="B219" refString="Scheffer, SJ, Lonsdale, O, 2011. Phytomyza omlandi spec. nov. - The first species of Agromyzidae (Diptera: Schizophora) reared from the family Gelsemiaceae (Asteridae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 113 (1): 42 - 49, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.113.1.42" title="Phytomyza omlandi spec. nov. - The first species of Agromyzidae (Diptera: Schizophora) reared from the family Gelsemiaceae (Asteridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4289/0013-8797.113.1.42" volume="113" year="2011">Scheffer and Lonsdale 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="A35BCEAFC13C7D942FCA4311DB5365D3" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" author="Scheffer, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="59 - 69" refId="B218" refString="Scheffer, SJ, Lewis, ML, Hebert, JB, Jacobsen, F, 2021. Diversity and Host Plant-Use in North American Phytomyza Holly Leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Colonization, Divergence, and Specificity in a Host-Associated Radiation. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 114 (1): 59 - 69, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" title="Diversity and Host Plant-Use in North American Phytomyza Holly Leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Colonization, Divergence, and Specificity in a Host-Associated Radiation." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" volume="114" year="2021">Scheffer et al. (2021)</bibRefCitation>
provided a thorough analysis of the host plant use and diversification in the group. Of the 12 Nearctic species in this group, 
<taxonomicName id="53182E27844E98B0D10C45C8D95DECEE" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. ilicis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="ilicis">
<emphasis id="A4657687E6F357AE7E937E3CF67181F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. ilicis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was introduced into the western Nearctic from Europe and eleven native species occur in the eastern United States. An additional undescribed species from Florida and North Carolina mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation id="19CDDC6980B97958E868D0AEF41DF56C" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" author="Scheffer, SJ" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="59 - 69" refId="B218" refString="Scheffer, SJ, Lewis, ML, Hebert, JB, Jacobsen, F, 2021. Diversity and Host Plant-Use in North American Phytomyza Holly Leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Colonization, Divergence, and Specificity in a Host-Associated Radiation. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 114 (1): 59 - 69, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" title="Diversity and Host Plant-Use in North American Phytomyza Holly Leafminers (Diptera: Agromyzidae): Colonization, Divergence, and Specificity in a Host-Associated Radiation." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/aesa/saaa034" volume="114" year="2021">Scheffer et al. (2021)</bibRefCitation>
on 
<taxonomicName id="60633F1ED9B5EF29C729CF8BECF1C277" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="Ilex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ilex amelanchier" order="Aquifoliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amelanchier">
<emphasis id="A5AF97605238AFDDD456C06B68C18ABC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ilex amelanchier</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not considered here. Nine of the eleven described native species occur in the Delmarva states: 
<taxonomicName id="33D785986C3F1F34C10867B5E41B2BD1" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. ditmani" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="ditmani">
<emphasis id="AA8E83F332B31B4BB021A027AB3E52E5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. ditmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0E2BC57FB3E4FD238FA3A600B0686B3D" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. glabricola" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="glabricola">
<emphasis id="F0C6670238624ED164CFA4E79E29990A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. glabricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="FEED7B534D3EF24A57B13B5646BC2529" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. ilicicola" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="ilicicola">
<emphasis id="61E5BFB7010EB504F481BDA3D1020F94" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. ilicicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D46D9EF018542BBE958D4B8B9454A591" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. leslieae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="leslieae">
<emphasis id="AFDBEE869B5568038D14B73CB4490316" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. leslieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5CDEEB0A4389AF650E7D727506DEFBAC" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. lineata" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="lineata">
<emphasis id="5BD72F652D5F1741DB266056B94F92B9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. lineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E07769A8B790BDFD8AEF5E0285833293" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. nemopanthi" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nemopanthi">
<emphasis id="D62E3903DC8E9A4E061AA232C30865A8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. nemopanthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5496C59B645E0223D9C17D585B0326ED" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. opacae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="opacae">
<emphasis id="373B01077631B0A1D5130E8767DD5D78" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. opacae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C7E1E0FCEF190C639C7E44EA90BC7997" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. verticillatae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="verticillatae">
<emphasis id="1142254459366E637CFF625D847EC594" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. verticillatae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="876930A1410E9C3D5CA387963AC41F51" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. wiggii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="wiggii">
<emphasis id="DB4F79F920DCD63997907DE59FB47FA4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. wiggii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="751B3D089063200DC34651569F32ACFA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species group is tentatively treated as monophyletic on the basis of 
<taxonomicName id="A99B30CE8C4BEF42F4F6CE97FFDE2225" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aquifoliaceae" genus="Ilex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ilex" order="Aquifoliales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7CCC5C9D77A0363369E064BB34FB0D65" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ilex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-feeding, widely separated posterior ocelli, and overall genitalic morphology. The eleven native Nearctic species are further allied on the basis of a subrectangular ocellar tubercle and a bump above the anus on the epandrium (
<bibRefCitation id="43EF6E303FC32CD76C6B3EC74D6A54FA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Entomological Society of America" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1183 - 1206" refId="B145" refString="Lonsdale, O, Scheffer, SJ, 2011. Revision of the Holly leaf-miners in the Nearctic (Phytomyza: Agromyzidae). Annals of the Entomological Society of America 104 (6): 1183 - 1206, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" title="Revision of the Holly leaf-miners in the Nearctic (Phytomyza: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1603/AN11008" volume="104" year="2011">Lonsdale and Scheffer 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
